Under adiabatic conditions, the total enthalpy of reaction (ΔH° = 286 kJ mol−1) must be provided as electrical energy. Hence, the thermo-neutral cell potential (the potential at which there is no temperature change under adiabatic conditions) will be −1.48 V. If heat is supplied reversibly from the ambient surroundings at 298.15 K (isothermal), the minimum electrical energy required will therefore be the Gibbs energy of reaction and the minimum cell potential required will be −1.23 V. Therefore, this value will be used in this analysis and for convenience the negative sign will be dropped henceforth: Erxn=−Ecell=1.23V\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
